Another possible trope/"cliché" that no one seems to have pointed out yet is this:

> A nation set on Earth that is mostly or completely situated on a fictional landmass or a collection of fictional landmasses, regardless of size.

There's nothing wrong with it, of course, but it seems to be quite common. Some nations that are manifestations of it include:

> Astoria
> Western Fardelshufflestein
> Gandoor
> Aikoland
> Mobius and the Biscay

There certainly is a whole lot more of them out there.

Zeloria wrote:Even more bonus points if world history stayed exactly the same even tough there is an entirely new landmass.


At the end of the day, alternate history that isn't about a specific scenario and which doesn't take place under a short amount of time has a tendency to be a fool's errand. In the long run, the genre is closer to fantasy as it's speculation built upon more speculations for scenarios which start off difficult to guess-stimate and whose consequences would end up branching off even more. This is especially true of settings with Points of Divergence that go further back in time.

I try to make LP look realistic, but it's anything but. My biggest sin is that LP's existence screwing up the Atlantic Slave Trade but modern history running it's usual course, as you've said.
